        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                <date>Feb 16th 5624</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Dr J. I. Cohen</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dr Sir</p>
            <p>By rights I ought not to have noticed the report which reached me<lb/> respecting the
                hospital movement in <placeName>baltimore</placeName><add>?</add>; for if people do
                not<lb/> choose to inform the conductors of Hebrew periodicals of their<lb/> doings,
                I do not see any necessity on the part of the conductors<lb/> of these to bother
                themselves about what has not been communicated<lb/>
                <sic>officiallyy</sic>. I really do not see the propriety in the people of<lb/>
                <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>
                <del>?</del> hardly ever sending me a line respecting any thing<lb/> taking place
                among them; in this the reformer, the <hi rend="underline"><sic>moderador</sic></hi>
                and<lb/> orthodox are alike; it seems the Occident with its editor are of<lb/> no
                use to them. It is otherwise with the Israelite; this<lb/>
                <add>blank</add> edited by the gentlemanly of polished<lb/>
                <add>blank</add> has its favorite<add>?</add> in large numbers. If you<lb/>
                <add>blank</add> on the old proverb have <sic>I</sic><add>?</add> “a fellow-feeling
                makes us<lb/> wondrous kind.” It is not joke what I say. I felt the reverse of<lb/>
                pleased to receive the first and only information of the hospital<lb/> movement from
                a person who had been in <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>, or rather from<lb/> one
                who heard it from another. They say “reported” to some and<lb/> some to me. It is
                not fair<add>?</add> and those who labor for the <sic>Israelit</sic><lb/> in this
                country, if their treatment that <add>blank</add> mine<lb/> have another cause for
                complaint, nay disgust for the cruel <sic>neglec</sic><lb/> with which they are
                uniformly treated.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">But a truce to complaining, which I am certain will produce no<lb/>
                remedy. <sic>let</sic> me resort to your request <del>?</del> retired<lb/> last
                evening at nine P. M. (your letter reached me at ½ p.5 P.M.<lb/> on Dr
                    <add>blank</add> and he kindly lent me the accompanying volume, at<lb/> the same
                time stating that $4 would buy it. I thought the hint</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>about the price not very polite; while it is an offer, which you need<lb/> not mind
                however, as you can at your leisure return the book to<lb/> me, when I will restore
                it to <sic>it</sic> owner, <sic>It</sic> sounded however, like<lb/>
                <persName>Ephron's</persName> disinterestedness, in offering a piece of land for
                nothing<lb/> valued at 400 shekels; thought the present is only the<lb/> percent in
                greenbacks; a great difference truly.</p>
            <p>I hope you may soon succeed in erecting a building of enough dimen<lb/>sions for all
                    <add>blank</add>; since it is a cruelty to leave our<lb/> poor to the mercy of
                Christians who use all the means at their<lb/> command to affect conversions while
                they professedly attend to the<lb/> bodily wants of the sufferers. This has proved
                in <placeName>America</placeName> no<lb/> less than in
                <placeName>Europe</placeName>; and I rejoice therefore at every effort made to<lb/>
                lessen the evil.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Regarding a contribution of <sic>5000Dollars</sic> from here; though
                stated<lb/> by you seemingly as a jest may prove a reality if the proper means<lb/>
                be resorted to <sic>tA</sic><add>?</add> committee of your associates may with
                perfect<lb/> propriety propose joint action between
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> &amp; <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>,
                and<lb/> offer the former a share and vote in the management provided a<lb/> certain
                amount in subscription to the hospital fund and in <sic>sufficie</sic><lb/>
                contribution to the annual expenses be secured here.<sic>My</sic> cooperation<lb/>
                in urging the plan you can calculate on; though I regret <sic>saty</sic><lb/> of
                means. <sic>absence</sic>. <sic>had</sic> I the pecuniary ability to start a
                liberal<lb/> subscription, it could require no prompting to commence the work
                this<lb/> day. But I have little to give, I am as you are perhaps <sic>awre</sic>,
                    <sic>engage</sic><lb/> in <sic>anew</sic>
                <sic>enterprize</sic>, to form a publication fund, to print books as<lb/> far
                    <sic>ar</sic> the contributions will reach. I have set up about 240 pages<lb/>
                of <persName>Miss G. Aguilar's</persName> Jewish Faith, and hope to complete the
                present<lb/> series of books sooner <sic>tha</sic> when the mechanics can be
                obtained<lb/> as at present they work so slowly that I know not how to promise a</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>completion of the works. From <placeName>Baltimore</placeName> as yet I have had no
                    <sic>res</sic><lb/> response only from Dr <add>blank</add> who writes that he
                cannot obtain any<lb/> aid for same. However I hope to come down after a while in
                person,<lb/> and then see what I can do. The idea, it strikes me is a good one,<lb/>
                as only when people are so to say partners in literary <sic>enterprizes</sic><lb/>
                can they be induced to read, as they then do not want to lay out<lb/> their money
                without reaping the benefit.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Give my <del>?</del> best regards to all at home, and accept
                the<lb/> assurance of my regard old for yourself and family.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Truly yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="Envelope Postmarked:"><date>Feb 22</date>,
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
            <p rend="Addressed to:"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <addressee>Dr Joshua I Cohen</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>115 N Charles Street</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Maryland</placeName>
            </p>
